english:
  title: On Moon and River
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among the Buddhist monks of recent times, none is more renowned than Lazy Hermit. His name was "Hall of River and Moon," taking its meaning from how image and form respond to the workings of heaven. From this arose a tradition where his followers adopted water and moon in their own names—taking the lesser forms as Stream and Brook, the greater as Lake and Sea. Water exists in infinite variety, yet the moon shines unchanging. So too with people: though some possess wisdom and others lack it, all share an essential goodness. Truly, he chose his metaphor well.

    Now, the Bright Mirror has adopted the name "Moon and River," simply reversing the Lazy Hermit's own. But tell me—can the river and moon belong to the Lazy Hermit alone? The moon hangs in heaven for all with eyes to see. The river flows on earth for all with mouths to drink. How much more so the nature dwelling in human hearts! The essence the Lazy Hermit embodied lives in me as surely as in him—it belongs to no one privately. So even if I take what he named himself and invert it for my own calling, why should this not be fitting?

    Moreover, in this exchange—Moon-River and River-Moon—there emerges of itself the distinction between essence and function. When we say "Moon-River," we trace outward from function to find its root in essence. When we say "River-Moon," we move inward from essence to manifest in function. Yet essence and function spring from one source; above and below know no separation. The Great Master practices this contemplation: keeping the mind's essence ever clear and luminous, letting its responsive function accord with each arising without discord—like the moon illuminating the river, like the river receiving the moon's light. Whether I am called Moon-River or River-Moon, both are equally so.
  footnotes:
    - Lazy Hermit (懶翁) was a prominent Korean Buddhist monk of the Goryeo period, known for his philosophical depth and the poetic names he inspired among his followers.
    - The play between 江月 (river-moon) and 月江 (moon-river) carries philosophical significance in Buddhist thought regarding the relationship between essence (體) and function (用).
    - The reference to 'Bright Mirror' appears to be the dedicatee or subject of this piece, another monk or practitioner adopting their spiritual name.
